{"parse":{"title":"Board shear","pageid":12419784,"revid":782680944,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Boardshear_labeled.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Boardshear_labeled.jpg/250px-Boardshear_labeled.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"287\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Boardshear_labeled.jpg/375px-Boardshear_labeled.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Boardshear_labeled.jpg/500px-Boardshear_labeled.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"784\" data-file-height=\"900\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Boardshear_labeled.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Board shear</div></div></div>\n<p>Used extensively in <a href=\"/wiki/Bookbinding\" title=\"Bookbinding\">bookbinding</a>, a <b>board shear</b> is a large, hand-operated machine for cutting board or paper.  Like <a href=\"/wiki/Scissors\" title=\"Scissors\">scissors</a>, a board shear uses two blades to apply <a href=\"/wiki/Shear_stress\" title=\"Shear stress\">shear stress</a> exceeding the paper's <a href=\"/wiki/Shear_strength\" title=\"Shear strength\">shear strength</a> in order to cut.  The stationary blade forms the edge of the cutting table, with the moving blade mounted on a cutting arm.  Originally known as a table gauge shear because its gauge allowed the cutting of consistently-sized materials, the board shear resembles a larger version of the paper cutters commonly found in offices.\n</p><p>The earliest known reference to a board shear comes from an 1842 supplement to <i><a href=\"/wiki/Penny_Magazine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Penny Magazine\">Penny Magazine</a></i>, titled <i>A Day at a Bookbinder's</i>, which included a drawing of a board shear with many of the major developments already present.  An 1854 article on the history of bookbinding from <i>The Bookbinder's Trade Circular</i> describes early board shears, and places their development in \"about 1836\"; credit for the invention is ascribed to Warren De La Rue in the <i>Reports of the Juries</i> from the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Exhibition\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Great Exhibition\">Great Exhibition of 1851</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Many modifications of the basic design were made in the 19th century, with changes such as rack-and-pinion adjustment for the outer gauge<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and improved clamp bars.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  By the late 19th century, board shears were substantively the same as modern machines, and many 19th-century board shears are still in use today.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2007)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Board_shear&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Middleton, Bernard (1996). <i>A History of English Craft Bookbinding Technique</i>. Oak Knoll Press &amp; <a href=\"/wiki/British_Library\" title=\"British Library\">The British Library</a>. pp.&#160;232\u2013234. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-884718-28-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-884718-28-0\">1-884718-28-0</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+History+of+English+Craft+Bookbinding+Technique&amp;rft.pages=232-234&amp;rft.pub=Oak+Knoll+Press+%26+The+British+Library&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.isbn=1-884718-28-0&amp;rft.aulast=Middleton&amp;rft.aufirst=Bernard&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABoard+shear\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Brombacher, C. U.S. Patent 43634, 1864.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Robinson, J.T. U.S. Patent 225871, 1880.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<p><cite class=\"citation web\">Harrison, Gary. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.indiana.edu/~libpres/manual/tools/boardshear.html\">\"Board Shear\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Indiana_University\" title=\"Indiana University\">Indiana University</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-07-24</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Board+Shear&amp;rft.pub=Indiana+University&amp;rft.aulast=Harrison&amp;rft.aufirst=Gary&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.indiana.edu%2F~libpres%2Fmanual%2Ftools%2Fboardshear.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABoard+shear\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span>\n</p><p><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"ht